# Just Wear It
### An AI-Powered Outfit Recommendation System
**Alba Quintas Núñez · CPSC 4580 · Spring 2026**

---

## Motivation

In the first class of the course, Professor Slade mentioned that he did not spend time deciding what to wear each day because he did not find it useful. In reality, people spend a lot of time thinking about what to wear. According to a 2016 poll conducted by Marks & Spencer, women spend an average of 17 minutes a day on this decision, while men dedicate 13 minutes daily. For women, this adds up to four full days a year, and for men, three.

Just Wear It automates this decision. It focuses on prioritizing the goals one may have for an outfit. Once the user provides pictures of the clothes in their closet, the program matches them to create outfits they will like — and saves them between 13 and 17 minutes a day.

---

## What is this?

Just Wear It is an automated decision system that chooses your daily outfit for you. You upload photos of your clothes, set your preferences for the day, and the program recommends a complete outfit with a full explanation of every decision it made. It takes into account all the factors I consider when choosing an outfit, letting the user set those parameters as goals for the decision.

The system goes beyond existing apps like Pureple, Fits, and Alta, which only consider weather and your closet inventory. Pureple mentions that it "combines real-time weather data with your closet inventory to suggest ideal outfits for the day." The Fits app adds the event you might be attending. Alta claims personalized recommendations but, like Pureple, only considers clothes and weather.

As a fashion lover, I can attest that many other factors must be considered. These metrics fluctuate from person to person, so without considering them all, we cannot provide a truly personalized suggestion. Pereira et al. (2022) highlight this issue, raising concerns about "personalized suggestions" on fashion websites — these tools do not place enough importance on customers' personality traits.

Just Wear It models the full human outfit decision process: personal style, occasion, formality, color preferences, event themes, what you wore yesterday, comfort vs. style tradeoffs, and real-time weather.

---

## What is interesting and important about it

**The recommendation decision is made entirely by a Python scoring algorithm. The Anthropic API is used only for two peripheral tasks: analyzing clothing photos (perception) and generating natural language explanations (narration). The decision of which outfit to recommend is never delegated to the API — it is not a black box.**

What makes this system academically interesting:

- **Multi-criteria decision system** — The recommender scores every wardrobe item against 11 weighted parameters — occasion, formality, personal style, comfort, boldness, weather, event theme, preferred colors, avoided colors, forbidden color combinations, and outfit repetition avoidance — while two additional parameters (style mood for today and layering preference) shape the explanation and outerwear inclusion respectively.
- **More parameters than any commercial app** — goes beyond weather + inventory to include personal style, boldness, layering preference, event themes, color avoidance combinations, and outfit repetition avoidance.
- **Theme-driven recommendation** — typing "garden party", "Audrey Hepburn", "polka dot party", or "The Great Gatsby" activates a matching system that directly scans item descriptions for theme words, giving matching items a score override.
- **Fuzzy style matching** — related styles get partial credit (e.g. "romantic" counts towards "bohemian"), and style is inferred from item descriptions as well as tags.
- **Fully explainable decisions** — every recommendation includes a natural language explanation grounded in the scoring breakdown, not generated independently.

