## Use of AI

In this project, I used Claude to create a more robust recommendation system, design the entire front end of the demo, and assist with the explanations in this document. First, I created pseudocode for the program's different .py files. Then, I used Claude to improve the program's efficacy.

One example of this was the computer vision part of the program. Initially, I realized that, depending on the lighting and orientation of the uploaded pictures, the AI analysis would misidentify the type of clothing (bottom, top, outerwear, etc.) or the color or fabric. After attempting to fix this issue, I came up with the idea of allowing users to edit the descriptions of their wardrobe items. This way, users do not need to worry about taking pictures with the best lighting, and we can account for scenarios in which the API cannot identify denim and other fabrics. Initially, this impacted the recommendation system's score system because the program was not classifying some clothes correctly.

Another feature that I improved with AI was the theme analyzer. Initially, I tried to use a Pinterest API to provide context about the theme selected by the user (e.g., color palette or style) for the recommender, as a person choosing an outfit might do. However, using their API required applying for developer access. Therefore, I decided to have the program use the Anthropic API to analyze themes in real time.

Using AI to implement the weather feature was also very efficient. I did not know about the Open-Meteo API before starting the project. After creating some pseudocode and collaborating with Claude, I was able to access the user's live weather (if they allow the program to use their location) and incorporate it into the recommendations.

---

## Project Structure Notes

- No database is used. All wardrobe data lives in memory for the session and resets when the server restarts.
- Uploaded images are saved to an `uploads/` folder on disk.
- The `.env` file containing the API key is not committed to GitHub (excluded by `.gitignore`) but is included in the ZIP submission.
- The program is designed to run locally (`http://127.0.0.1:5000`) for demonstration purposes.

